notesStmt.note: This is an example of a Gospel Lectionary written in the archaic, majuscule form of Greek letters. Liturgical books were inherently conservative and therefore commonly retained such antiquated writing. The scribe, a certain monk Theodore, has recorded his name in a verse at the end of the volume (fol. 179v). A leaf removed from this manuscript ca. 1900 is now in Sofia, National Library of Republic of Bulgaria NBKM Gr. 2.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Greek, Ancient (to 1453).

msItem.title: Gospel Lectionary
msItem.note: Fols. 1r-49v: readings for the weeks of John; fols. 50r-57v: readings for the weekends of Matthew; fols. 58r-81v: readings for the weekends of Luke; fols. 82r-129v: readings for Paschal Week; fols. 121v-128r: readings for the Hours of Good Friday; fols. 130r-173r: readings for the feast days from September 1 to August 31; fols. 178v-179v: list of readings for various occasions

colophon.note: Πένητα σώζε, Χ(ριστ)έ, τῷ γεγραφώτι, Θεοδώρῳ μοναστ(ῇ) καὶ ξένῳ τῶν δικαίων.
Peneta soze, Christe, to gegraphoti, Theodoro monaste kai xeno ton dikaion.
Christ, save the poor scribe Theodore, monk and stranger to righteousness.

supportDesc.foliation: Twentieth-century pencil foliation in upper right corners of rectos (followed here); nineteenth-century ink pagination in middle of upper margins

layoutDesc.layout: Hardpoint; writing stands on ruled lines

handDesc.handNote: Upright pointed majuscule in brown ink; one hand throughout manuscript; second hand added the ekphionetic notation, titles, liturgical notes, and initials
